% % <><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><>
% \section*{Lay abstract}
% % <><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><>
% Shifted phenology with climate change has extended the vegetative growing season, which is widely expected to increase tree growth. Multiple recent studies, however, have failed to find this relationship and suggested shifts in drought or competition may prevent increased growth. Here, we ask if trees grow more with longer seasons in an environment where drought and competition are limited. We aim to answer this question by leveraging 9 years of vegetative phenology data from two studies located in an urban arboretum and by relating it to tree growth (Figure \ref{fig:chaptersDesign}). We found contrasting evidence that trees grow more during longer seasons. Nine of our species did not change their growth; one grew less at its adult stage but more at its juvenile stage, and two additional species grew more with longer seasons. These responses increased when using the calendar instead of the thermal growing season. Our main findings demonstrate that tree growth responses with climate change may be more complex than previously suggested. The shifts in response to season lengths were not massive, and when they happened it was from juvenile more than mature trees.

% \begin{figure}[h!]
% \includegraphics[width=0.85\textwidth]{../../notes/chaptersDesign/chaptersDesign.pdf}
% \caption{Overview of the age class, species, provenance of the trees used in each study along with the type of study each project consists of. The colored lines represent the period of the growth data and the shaded areas are the phenological data. Both are colour-coded by project. Each phylogram illustrates the species used in each project. The map illustrates the four different provenances used in Wildchrokie, and the star represents the location of Wildchrokie and CoringTreespotters.}
% \label{fig:chaptersDesign}
% \end{figure}


% <><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><>
\section*{Research questions}
% <><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><>
\begin{enumerate}
\item Did growth change across years, and if so what cue had the largest effects?
\item How do species ring widths vary with thermal season vs calendar season?
\item Does the previous year cumulated GDD influence the following year's growth?
\item How do species spring and autumn phenophases shift with the temperature of different seasons?
\item Does growth change across provenances?
\end{enumerate}

% <><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><>
\section*{Results}
% <><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><>
\begin{enumerate}
\item Summary results
  \begin{enumerate}
  \item Wildchrokie includes four deciduous tree species from four sites with \Sexpr{nrow(emp)} complete growing seasons (GS)
  
  \item Phenology data span three years from 2018 to 2020 with \Sexpr{nrow(empfullsos)} leafout and \Sexpr{nrow(empfulleos)} budset observations
  \item The earliest leafout day of year was \Sexpr{min(emp$leafout)} (\Sexpr{emp$year[which.min(emp$leafout)]}) and the latest, \Sexpr{max(emp$leafout)} (\Sexpr{emp$year[which.min(emp$leafout)]}). 
  \item The earliest budset day of year was \Sexpr{min(emp$budset)} (\Sexpr{emp$year[which.min(emp$budset)]}) and the latest, \Sexpr{max(emp$budset)} (\Sexpr{emp$year[which.min(emp$budset)]})
  
  \item GS thermal sum ranged from 
  \Sexpr{round(min(emp$pgsGDD5),1)} GDD ({\Ball} in \Sexpr{emp$year[which.min(emp$pgsGDD5)]}) to 
  \Sexpr{round(max(emp$pgsGDD5),1)} GDD, ({\Ainc} in \Sexpr{emp$year[which.max(emp$pgsGDD5)]})
  
  \item No drought for the three years except in 2020, where a moderate drought ramped up to a severe drought in September.
  
  \item GSL ranged from 
  \Sexpr{min(emp$pgsGSL)} days ({\Ball} in \Sexpr{emp$year[which.min(emp$pgsGSL)]}) to 
  \Sexpr{max(emp$pgsGSL)} days ({\Ainc} in \Sexpr{emp$year[which.max(emp$pgsGSL)]})
  
  \item Annual ring widths across years varied from 
  \Sexpr{min(emp$lengthMM)} mm ({\Ball} in \Sexpr{emp$year[which.min(emp$lengthMM)]}) to 
  \Sexpr{max(emp$lengthMM)} mm ({\Bpop} in \Sexpr{emp$year[which.max(emp$lengthMM)]}). 
\end{enumerate}

\item Did growth change across years, and if so what cue had the largest effects?
  \begin{enumerate}
  \item Growth was highest on average in 2018, but no cue dominated (it was neither: the wettest; the driest; the shortest; the latest SOS; the earliest EOS nor the highest thermal sum)
  \item Growth was lowest on average in 2020 and that year was: the driest; the shortest; the latest SOS and EOS and had the highest thermal sum
  \end{enumerate}

\item How do species ring widths vary with thermal season vs calendar season?
  \begin{enumerate}
  \item A later start of season decreased growth for two species 
  ({\Ainc}: $\beta = $ \Sexpr{bspp_df2_sos$fit_bspp[which(bspp_df2_sos$spp_name %in% "Alnus incana")]}, $UI_{90}$
  [\Sexpr{bspp_df2_sos$fit_bspp_per5[which(bspp_df2_sos$spp_name %in% "Alnus incana")]}, 
  \Sexpr{bspp_df2_sos$fit_bspp_per95[which(bspp_df2_sos$spp_name %in% "Alnus incana")]}] and 
  {\Bpop}: $\beta = $ \Sexpr{bspp_df2_sos$fit_bspp[which(bspp_df2_sos$spp_name %in% "Betula populifolia")]}, $UI_{90}$[\Sexpr{bspp_df2_sos$fit_bspp_per5[which(bspp_df2_sos$spp_name %in% "Betula populifolia")]}, \Sexpr{bspp_df2_sos$fit_bspp_per95[which(bspp_df2_sos$spp_name %in% "Betula populifolia")]}]) (Figure \ref{fig:wcmuplotbspp}c (Table \ref{tab:wc_slope_table}).
  
  \item A later end of season decreased growth only for {\Ainc} 
  ($\beta = $ \Sexpr{bspp_df2_eos$fit_bspp[which(bspp_df2_eos$spp_name %in% "Alnus incana")]}, $UI_{90}$
  [\Sexpr{bspp_df2_eos$fit_bspp_per5[which(bspp_df2_eos$spp_name %in% "Alnus incana")]}, \Sexpr{bspp_df2_eos$fit_bspp_per95[which(bspp_df2_eos$spp_name %in% "Alnus incana")]}]) (Figure \ref{fig:wcmuplotbspp}d (Table \ref{tab:wc_slope_table}).
  
  \item Longer thermal season increased growth only for {\Bpap} 
  ($\beta = $ \Sexpr{bspp_df2$fit_bspp[which(bspp_df2$spp_name %in% "Betula papyrifera")]}, $UI_{90}$
[\Sexpr{bspp_df2$fit_bspp_per5[which(bspp_df2$spp_name %in% "Betula papyrifera")]}, 
\Sexpr{bspp_df2$fit_bspp_per95[which(bspp_df2$spp_name %in% "Betula papyrifera")]}]) (Figure \ref{fig:wcmuplotbspp}a (Table \ref{tab:wc_slope_table}).

  \item But longer calendar season increased growth for two additional species
  (\Ainc: $\beta = $ \Sexpr{bspp_df2_gsl$fit_bspp[which(bspp_df2_gsl$spp_name %in% "Alnus incana")]}, $UI_{90}$[\Sexpr{bspp_df2_gsl$fit_bspp_per5[which(bspp_df2_gsl$spp_name %in% "Alnus incana")]}, \Sexpr{bspp_df2_gsl$fit_bspp_per95[which(bspp_df2_gsl$spp_name %in% "Alnus incana")]}],
\Ball: $\beta = $ \Sexpr{bspp_df2_gsl$fit_bspp[which(bspp_df2_gsl$spp_name %in% "Betula alleghaniensis")]}, $UI_{90}$[\Sexpr{bspp_df2_gsl$fit_bspp_per5[which(bspp_df2_gsl$spp_name %in% "Betula alleghaniensis")]}, \Sexpr{bspp_df2_gsl$fit_bspp_per95[which(bspp_df2_gsl$spp_name %in% "Betula alleghaniensis")]}] and
\Bpap: $\beta = $ \Sexpr{bspp_df2_gsl$fit_bspp[which(bspp_df2_gsl$spp_name %in% "Betula papyrifera")]}, $UI_{90}$[\Sexpr{bspp_df2_gsl$fit_bspp_per5[which(bspp_df2_gsl$spp_name %in% "Betula papyrifera")]}, \Sexpr{bspp_df2_gsl$fit_bspp_per95[which(bspp_df2_gsl$spp_name %in% "Betula papyrifera")]}]) (Figure \ref{fig:wcmuplotbspp}b (Table \ref{tab:wc_slope_table}).

  \item Calendar season had a bigger effect on growth than the thermal season (Figure \ref{fig:bsppZscored})
  
  \end{enumerate}

\item Does the previous year cummulated GDD influence the following year's growth?
  \begin{enumerate}
  \item Growth decreased for all species with current year GDD
  \item But growth decreased for only two species with previous year GDD
  \end{enumerate}
  
\item How do species spring and autumn phenophases shift with the temperature of different seasons?
  \begin{enumerate}
  \item \textit{results in progress so this is just an example of where it would belong:} warmer winter delayed leafout, but warmer springs advanced leafout.
  \end{enumerate}

\item Does growth change across sites?
  \begin{enumerate}
  \item Growth did not change across any site (Figure \ref{fig:wcmuplotasite}) (Table \ref{tab:wc_asite_table}).
  \end{enumerate}

\end{enumerate}


% Figure mu across all species and climate predictors
\begin{figure}[!ht]
\includegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth]{../../analyses/figures/growthModelsMain/muALLbspp.pdf}
\caption{Model slope parameters across the different model predictors for Wildchrokie species. GDD represent the accumulated growing degree days between leafout and budset (a) the models estimates shows log ring width change per 10 average spring days GDD (\Sexpr{wcgddscale}). GSL is the number of days between leafout and budset (b). SOS represent the start of season, which is leafout (c) and EOS, the end of season through budset (d). All predictors were fit using the same model and number of observations, with only the independent variable changing. The dots represent the mean of the posterior distribution, the thick lines the 50\% uncertainty intervals (UI) and the thinner lines, the 90\% UI.}
\label{fig:wcmuplotbspp}
\end{figure}

% Wildchrokie site mu plot
\begin{figure}[!ht]
\includegraphics[width=1\textwidth]{../../analyses/figures/growthModelsMain/asiteMap.pdf}
\caption{The effect of sites on growth across a latitudinal gradient. (a) Model intercept parameters for each site with growing degree days (GDD) as the predictor. The dots represent the mean of the posterior distribution, the thick lines the 50\% uncertainty intervals (UI) and the thinner lines, the 90\% UI. The sites are color-coded from (b), th map showing their locations.}
\label{fig:wcmuplotasite}
\end{figure}

